04074nam a22004815i 9780226470795DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264707957 a10.7208/97802264707952doi  a(DE-B1597)524581  a(OCoLC)994502780  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a523.430721 aLane, K. Maria D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGeographies of Mars :bSeeing and Knowing the Red Planet /cK. Maria D. Lane. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b39 halftones, 6 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tONE. Understanding Mars: Sensation, Science, and Geography -- tTWO. Representing Scientific Data: Cartographic Inscription and Visual Authority -- tTHREE. Representing Scientific Sites: Vision and Fieldwork at the Mountain Observatories -- tFOUR. Representing Scientists: Heroism, Adventure, and the Geographical Outlook -- tFIVE. Placing the Red Planet: Meanings in the Martian Landscape -- tSIX. Toward a Cultural Geography of Mars: Imaginative Geography and the Superior Martian -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the first maps of Mars, published by an Italian astronomer in 1877, with its pattern of canals, fueled belief in intelligent life forms on the distant red planet—a hope that continued into the 1960s. Although the Martian canals have long since been dismissed as a famous error in the history of science, K. Maria D. Lane argues that there was nothing accidental about these early interpretations. Indeed, she argues, the construction of Mars as an incomprehensibly complex and engineered world both reflected and challenged dominant geopolitical themes during a time of major cultural, intellectual, political, and economic transition in the Western world. Geographies of Mars telescopes in on a critical period in the development of the geographical imagination, when European imperialism was at its zenith and American expansionism had begun in earnest. Astronomers working in the new observatories of the American Southwest or in the remote heights of the South American Andes were inspired, Lane finds, by their own physical surroundings and used representations of the Earth’s arid landscapes to establish credibility for their observations of Mars. With this simple shift to the geographer’s point of view, Lane deftly explains some of the most perplexing stances on Mars taken by familiar protagonists such as Percival Lowell, Alfred Russel Wallace, and Lester Frank Ward. A highly original exploration of geography’s spatial dimensions at the beginning of the twentieth century, Geographies of Mars offers a new view of the mapping of far-off worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMartians. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226470795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226470795.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles